liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian Electoral Commission says a record number of young and Indigenous Australians have enrolled to vote in the upcoming referendum. Figures from the AEC reveal almost 98 per cent of eligible Australians have registered to vote in the Indigenous Voice to Parliament referendum next month. A Voice to Parliament would act as an independent advisory body for First Nations people. Australian Electoral Commissioner, Tom Rogers, says the registration figures are a great result. "It's criticial that all Australians have their chance to have their say," he says. "Youth enrolment is at the highest rate its ever been for an electoral event and the same for estimated indigenous enrolment so it's a great outcome for all Australians and it means that it will be a solid event and a solid outcome." Rogers says the referendum vote is a huge logistical event. "We'll be visiting well over 750 remote communities. I think last week we dispatched 160,000 ballot papers to our overseas missions - the largest in-person overseas vote that we've seen. "Big postal process is underway. I think as of yesterday we've had something like about 1.2 million applications for postal votes."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Record number of Australians enrol to vote in Voice referendum

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Hobart's popular winter tourist drawcard, Dark Mofo, has been cancelled for 2024. Festival organisers say they hope the "period of renewal" will set it up for a "full return" in 2025. Dark Mofo's new artistic director Chris Twite made the announcement on Hobart's waterfront this morning. He says two staples of the festival — the Winter Fest and Nude Solstice Swim — will still go ahead next year, but without the rest of the festival, after reaching an agreement with the state government. Next year was to be Twite's first Dark Mofo, after long-time artistic director Leigh Carmichael stepped down from the role following this year's festival. "Whilst it's a tough decision, it allows us the time to ensure we have a festival for another decade of darkness," Twite said. "It allows us to face, head-on, rising costs and changing conditions to ensure that future for a full return in 2025, and to lay the foundation for the festival for another decade."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: BREAKING: Hobart's Dark Mofo festival cancelled for 2024

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The federal government has revealed the country's first surplus in 15 years as the final budget outcome figures for the last year show a surplus of over $22 billion. It's the last Commonwealth budget surplus since Peter Costello’s 2007-08 budget and the last Labor government surplus since Paul Keating in 1989-90. That dramatic improvement is a result of strong commodity prices, and higher than expected income and company tax revenue, but the government says the surplus is also down to responsible economic management. Federal Treasurer Jim Chalmers says the government "delivered this surplus at the same time as providing billions of dollars in cost-of-living relief and making vital investments in the long-term growth of our economy". You can ready more about this story below:
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Federal government reveals $22 billion budget surplus

liveBlogPostPrepared.title: And here's the response from Chevron Australia

children.content: Following a Fair Work Commission recommendation today, a spokesperson from Chevron Australia has told the ABC:
Chevron Australia has consistently engaged in meaningful negotiations in an effort to finalise Enterprise Agreements with market competitive remuneration and conditions.
Today, we were provided a recommendation from Commissioner Riordan.
After considering the recommendation, Chevron has accepted the recommendation to resolve all outstanding issues and finalise the agreements.
We have informed the Commissioner of our position and written to the unions and other employee bargaining representatives confirming our acceptance.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Offshore Alliance members at Chevron endorsed a recommendation put by the Fair Work Commision at a late night mass meeting of over 350 workers. Offshore Alliance members from three Chevron gas facilities, Gorgon, Wheatstone Platform and Wheatstone Downstream met at 7pm WA time to consider a recommendation put to both Chevron and Offshore Alliance members yesterday morning by Commissioner Riordan. The proposed enterprise agreements, which incorporate the Commissioner's recommendations, contain substantial improvements in terms and conditions of employment including increased remuneration, job security, locked-in rosters, career progression and returning all employees to a 40 per cent roster. The Offshore Alliance will now work with Chevron to finalise the drafting of the three agreements and members will soon cease current industrial action The Offshore Alliance is an alliance between The Australian Workers’ Union (AWU) and the Maritime Union of Australia (MUA). Offshore Alliance spokesperson, AWU WA Secretary Brad Gandy, says Offshore Alliance members carefully considered Commissioner Riordan’s recommendation before endorsing it. “Commissioner Riordan’s recommendation contains substantial improvements in terms and conditions of employment including increased remuneration, job security, locked-in rosters, career progression and returning all employees to a 40% roster,” says Mr Gandy. “'The Offshore Alliance is a member-led union and at a late night mass meeting members endorsed the latest offer which incorporates the Fair Work Commission's recommendations. “The Offshore Alliance will now work with Chevron to finalise the drafting of the agreement and members will soon cease current industrial action."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Offshore Alliance members at Chevron endorse Fair Work Commission recommendation

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian share market has opened sharply lower, with investors concerned about global economic growth after the US Federal Reserve signaled interest rates would stay higher for longer. The ASX 200 was down 1.4 per cent or 100 points, to 6,965 points, by 10:15am AEST. All sectors were in the red in the first 15 mins of trade. Only 11 stocks were higher. Miners and education firms were leading the losses.
